**Which Pattern to Use --- Decision Guide**

+----------------------+----------------------+-----------------------+
| **Use RBAC           | **Use ABAC           | **Apply Least         |
| when\...**           | when\...**           | Privilege             |
|                      |                      | always\...**          |
+----------------------+----------------------+-----------------------+
| -   Users fall into  | -   Access depends   | -   When designing    |
|     a small number   |     on context:      |     any new role ---  |
|     of fixed job     |     time, location,  |     start with zero   |
|     functions        |     device, MFA      |     permissions       |
|                      |     status           |                       |
| -   Permissions are  |                      | -   When creating     |
|     the same for     | -   The same user    |     service accounts  |
|     everyone in a    |     needs different  |     or API keys       |
|     role             |     permissions on   |                       |
|                      |     different        | -   When granting     |
| -   The system has a |     resources        |     temporary         |
|     clear            |                      |     elevated access   |
|     org-chart-style  | -   You need to      |     --- set an expiry |
|     hierarchy        |     express rules    |                       |
|                      |     like \"own       | -   When reviewing    |
| -   You need simple, |     content only\"   |     existing          |
|     auditable access |     or \"own region  |     permissions ---   |
|     rules            |     only\"           |     remove anything   |
|                      |                      |     unused            |
| **Start here. Add    | -   You are          |                       |
| ABAC later if RBAC   |     implementing     | **Least Privilege is  |
| proves               |     OAuth 2.0 scopes | a constraint applied  |
| insufficient.**      |     for third-party  | to both RBAC and ABAC |
|                      |     access           | --- not an            |
|                      |                      | alternative to        |
|                      | **More powerful but  | them.**               |
|                      | requires centralised |                       |
|                      | policy management.** |                       |
+----------------------+----------------------+-----------------------+

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Juice Shop connection:** Juice Shop\'s /administration panel is
  accessible to any authenticated user --- it has no role check at all.
  This violates all three patterns simultaneously: RBAC (no role
  requirement), ABAC (no attribute check), and Least Privilege (all
  authenticated users implicitly have admin access). Find it by browsing
  to /#/administration after logging in as any user. Then examine the
  /api/Users endpoint in ZAP --- it returns all user records to any
  authenticated caller, with no ownership or role filter.

